  "text": "I identified all four Fetch API WebIDL interface files in mozilla-firefox/firefox repository and their corresponding C++ binding implementations.\n\n**Request Interface:**\n- WebIDL Definition: dom/webidl/Request.webidl\n- C++ Header: dom/fetch/Request.h\n- C++ Implementation: dom/fetch/Request.cpp\n- The Request class inherits from FetchBody<Request> and nsWrapperCache, implementing the WebIDL Request interface with methods for URL, method, headers, and other properties.\n\n**Response Interface:**\n- WebIDL Definition: dom/webidl/Response.webidl\n- C++ Header: dom/fetch/Response.h\n- C++ Implementation: dom/fetch/Response.cpp\n- The Response class inherits from FetchBody<Response> and nsWrapperCache, implementing the WebIDL Response interface with properties like type, url, status, headers, and clone methods.\n\n**Headers Interface:**\n- WebIDL Definition: dom/webidl/Headers.webidl\n- C++ Header: dom/fetch/Headers.h\n- C++ Implementation: dom/fetch/Headers.cpp\n- The Headers class is backed by InternalHeaders and provides methods like append, delete, get, has, and set for header manipulation, supporting iteration over header key-value pairs.\n\n**FetchEvent Interface:**\n- WebIDL Definition: dom/webidl/FetchEvent.webidl\n- C++ Header: dom/serviceworkers/ServiceWorkerEvents.h\n- C++ Implementation: dom/serviceworkers/ServiceWorkerEvents.cpp\n- FetchEvent is implemented as a service worker event that extends ExtendableEvent, providing access to the Request object, preload response, and client IDs, along with the respondWith() method for handling fetch events."
}

